node.text:
This nearly 340 year old book is called the Saducismus Triumphatus. 📚 It gives historical insight into what people believed about the paranormal, mediums, and the unexplained. 
To know that the witch trials in America were only a few hundred years ago is a stark reminder of the importance of tolerance and the dangers of misogyny. 

Edit: To be more concise, this book contains the first mention of a “witch bottle” counter-charm; there are certainly other older forms of counter-charms that’ve been documented. 😊

node.text:
With the end of 2020, we’ve found ourselves in a liminal state. From the Latin word Limen, or threshold, liminal states are transitional states. They’re between two things or situations. 

We face liminality all the time, in physical places and our own head spaces. Waiting rooms and hallways are defined as liminal, while other times they’re life events that destabilize our routines and structure. However it presents itself, it makes us feel particular emotions. 

In this video I’ll cover the fascinating middle-realm of liminality, how it relates to everyday life, and its surprising relationship to the paranormal. 

Wishing you all peaceful and safe holidays, and a better, healthier 2021. 💙

Thanks to my editor @clintxgodwin ☺️

node.text:
We see mediums today on television and in audiences using their mind-power to deliver messages from spirit guides.  This type of mediumship has popularized clairvoyance, and made ESP a widely recognized acronym.

But before there was mediumship in the way we know it, there was physical mediumship. It gained traction in the 1850’s with the emergence of a religious belief that the departed could communicate through mediums. 

Physical mediums of the time like Daniel Dunglas Home and Eusapia Palladino were said to channel physical phenomena. This included the levitation of objects, the emission of mysterious lights, and full-body manifestations of departed loved ones in the room. It sounds unbelievable,  but particularly in Home’s case, the sharpest minds of the time were sent to investigate the phenomena. They found no solid evidence of trickery despite rigorous and up-close investigation. 

Before the emergence of Spiritualism a couple hundred years ago, mediums still existed. They just went by different titles. Both physical and mental mediumistic feats were performed by people who were historically feared and revered. “The Cunning Folk”, as they were called in the fifteenth century, were individuals who dedicated themselves to healing their communities through spiritual practices. They used their intuition to help those going through difficult times, and while they weren’t widely understood, they were important. 
They usually lived on the outskirts of society and were consulted only when people needed them most. 

In the Bible, Saul consults the “Witch of Endor” to summon the spirit of the prophet Samuel, with great success. (1 Samuel 28:3–25) There are countless examples of mediums before Spiritualism - they just weren’t called mediums, and were generally persecuted with religious fervor. Even today, stigma exists around the subject because of thousands of years of misunderstanding. Mediums through history have validated people’s faith and helped them know that there’s more to life than what meets the eye. 

(Illustrations are from my 1st edition copy of the Saducismus  Triumphatus, c. 1681)

node.text: This clip from last night’s #LeadWithLove telethon made me smile! I auctioned off a reading with all proceeds going to @projectangelfood and got to catch up with Loni Love about our reading. Thanks to all of you who donated to feed those in need across LA. 💙

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Tyler Henry on July 17, 2021. May be an image of 2 people, people standing and indoor.

node.text: @projectangelfood’s #LeadWithLove event was a success! Over $1,000,000 raised for this incredible charity that prepares and delivers meals to people experiencing illness. 2,300 meals are prepared and delivered to people’s doors every single day.  Check them out on social media to see how you can help.

node.text: I couldn’t ask for a better dad. Pictured is a tricky stained glass piece he helped me cut with his tile saw — he always has a fix for everything! Wishing you all a happy Father’s Day. 💙

node.text: I’m ready to hit the road for the live tour again! 🚗💨Check out the link in my bio for tickets. We’re working with the local health guidelines of each venue to ensure that everyone has peace of mind and a fun evening. I’ll see you all soon!
